\begin_layout Standard
For the above reasons, we do not use the measurements in the high gas fractional
 flow regime for the estimation of the water relative permeability curves.
 In fact, we only use the data for low gas fractional flow (low quality)
 regime, at which the capillary pressure is lower and the flow of foam is
 dominated by the mobilization and trapping of bubbles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculated capillary number, using the following equation from Reynolds
 & Krevor,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{c}=\frac{H}{L}\frac{\Delta p}{\Delta p_{c}},\label{eq:capillary-number}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is plotted versus the measured liquid saturation in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:saturation-capillary-number"

\end_inset

.
 For the relatively homogeneous core in our study (see the porosity profile
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Porosity-profile"

\end_inset

), we use a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p_{c}$
\end_inset

 of 5000 Pa, which is arguably larger than the actual value of the critical
 capillary pressure difference.
 The points depicted with gray markers show the data for the high gas fractional
 flow regime.
 The colored points show the data for the low gas fractional flow regime.
 It is clear from this figure that at a constant capillary number, the measured
 liquid saturation changes with the surfactant concentration.
 This shows that our measurements that are used in the calculation of the
 water relative permeability are not affected by the capillary-viscous force
 interplay.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the reviewer has pointed out, reporting these values could have made
 it clear.
 Therefore, we decided follow the points raised by the reviewer and add
 a short appendix to the paper with the above analysis.
 
\end_layout

